  "prompt": "According to the first law of motion, external force stops a body in uniform motion. What force do I have if I stop a rolling pin.?",
  "response": "When you stop a rolling pin, you're applying an **external force** to change its state of motion, as described by **Newton's First Law of Motion**. Here's a breakdown of the forces involved:\n\n1. **Force You Apply**: \n   - **Hand or Muscle Force**: When you grab and stop the rolling pin, your hand exerts a force opposite to the direction of its motion. This is the primary force you apply to halt its movement.\n   \n2. **Frictional Forces**:\n   - **Friction Between Your Hand and the Rolling Pin**: This friction opposes the motion of the rolling pin and helps in bringing it to a stop.\n   - **Friction Between the Rolling Pin and the Surface**: If the rolling pin is in contact with a surface (like a countertop), friction between the pin and the surface also acts to slow it down.\n\n3. **Other Possible Forces**:\n   - **Air Resistance**: Although usually minimal for a rolling pin, air resistance can slightly contribute to slowing it down.\n\n**Example Scenario**:\n- If a rolling pin is moving across a countertop, and you decide to stop it, you might slide your hand along the pin's side. Your hand applies a force opposite to the pin's velocity. The combination of your applied force and the frictional forces between the pin and the countertop work together to decelerate and eventually stop the pin.\n\n**Key Point**:\n- The **external force** you apply (primarily through friction with your hand) is necessary to overcome the pin's inertia, which would otherwise keep it moving at a constant velocity.\n\nIn summary, **the force you use to stop the rolling pin is the external force applied by your hand, typically manifested as friction opposing its motion**. This external force changes the rolling pin's state from moving to stationary, in accordance with Newton's First Law of Motion.\n\n**References**:\n- [Newton's First Law of Motion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_first_law_of_motion)\n- [Forces and Motion](https://www.physicsclassroom.com/class/newtlaws/Lesson-1/Newton-s-First-Law)\n\nWhen you stop a rolling pin, you apply an external force\u2014typically a force opposite its motion through your hand\u2019s friction\u2014that opposes and halts its uniform motion in accordance with Newton\u2019s first law.",
